  "text": "Results were further adjusted in multivariable logistic regression for all of the significant risk factors found within the univariable analysis, and age (age, body mass index, skin type, alcohol use, The 83 melanomas within our cases represent 34 malignant melanomas, 45 melanomas in-situ, and 4 atypical junctional melanocytic proliferations; diagnoses were confirmed by a board-certified dermatopathologist. The majority of the melanomas were Clark level I (58.2%), with an overall mean Breslow depth of 0.36 mm, and range of 0.1 mm-0.60 mm. The majority of the cases were on the trunk (32.5%), and on the face (25.3%). In univariable analysis age, skin type, body mass index, cigarette use, pack years, alcohol use, benign prostatic hyperplasia medications, immunosuppression status, history of prostate cancer, and prostate cancer treatment were assessed for their potential to be risk factors for melanoma development (Table 1 ). Age was not significantly different between cases and controls with a mean of 67 years for melanoma males and 69 for non-melanoma males (p = 0.33). Fitzpatrick skin type II was the predominant skin type within both groups, however melanoma patients had 3.1 times the odds of having a skin type II than non-melanoma patients (p = 0.007 [95% CI 1. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ). Additionally, skin type III patients had 0.34 times the odds of having melanoma than the controls (p = 0.047 [95% CI 0.07, 0.9]). Cases had significantly higher body mass index than the controls (p = 0.018), however both groups fell into the overweight category.",
